Resource limits prevent sandboxed code from running forever or exhausting the
host. Each `exec()` call accepts a `timeout`, and when the budget elapses the
guest process is killed so a runaway program can never hang the host. The
timeout is the limit you reach for through the ergonomic `NodeRuntime` API
today; secure-exec enforces several more resource limits at the VM level, and
those are described at the end of this page.

## Limiting Execution Time

```ts
import { NodeRuntime } from "secure-exec";

const rt = await NodeRuntime.create();

try {
	// A normal program finishes well within the timeout budget.
	const ok = await rt.exec(`console.log("finished work");`, {
		timeout: 5000,
	});
	console.log("normal run:");
	console.log("  exitCode:", ok.exitCode);
	console.log("  stdout:", JSON.stringify(ok.stdout.trim()));

	// A runaway program (infinite loop) never returns on its own. The exec
	// timeout terminates the guest process after the budget elapses.
	const start = Date.now();
	const runaway = await rt.exec(`while (true) {}`, {
		timeout: 1000,
	});
	const elapsed = Date.now() - start;

	console.log("runaway run (timeout: 1000ms):");
	console.log("  exitCode:", runaway.exitCode);
	console.log("  elapsedMs:", elapsed);

	// A killed process exits non-zero; a clean exit would be 0.
	const terminated = runaway.exitCode !== 0;
	console.log(
		terminated
			? "runaway guest was terminated by the timeout"
			: "ERROR: runaway guest was NOT terminated",
	);

	if (!terminated) {
		process.exitCode = 1;
	}
} finally {
	await rt.dispose();
}
```

*[See Full Example](https://github.com/rivet-dev/secure-exec/tree/main/examples/docs/feat-resource-limits)*

Running it prints:

```text
normal run:
  exitCode: 0
  stdout: "finished work"
runaway run (timeout: 1000ms):
  exitCode: 137
  elapsedMs: 2506
runaway guest was terminated by the timeout
```

## Execution timeout

Pass `timeout` (in milliseconds) to `exec()` to bound how long a single guest
program may run. When the budget elapses, the guest process is killed and `exec()`
returns with a non-zero `exitCode` (`137`, i.e. `128 + SIGKILL`).

```ts
const runaway = await rt.exec(`while (true) {}`, {
	timeout: 1000,
});

console.log(runaway.exitCode); // 137 (terminated)
```

A program that finishes before the timeout returns its real exit code:

```ts
const ok = await rt.exec(`console.log("finished work");`, {
	timeout: 5000,
});

console.log(ok.exitCode); // 0
```

The same `timeout` option is available on `run()`.

## Other limits enforced by the VM

The execution `timeout` is the only resource limit exposed as a
`NodeRuntime.exec()` / `NodeRuntime.run()` option today, but it is not the only
limit secure-exec enforces. The VM applies a broader set of resource limits
configured at VM creation through the protocol's `VmLimits`
(`CreateVmConfig.limits`), including:

- **Memory**: a V8 heap limit (`jsRuntime.v8HeapLimitMb`) caps how much memory
  guest JavaScript may allocate, plus filesystem byte and inode caps for the
  virtual filesystem.
- **Payload and transfer limits**: caps on captured output, stdin buffering,
  event payload size, and `fetch()` response size bound how much data moves
  between the guest and the host.
- **CPU-time budget**: secure-exec can bound CPU usage (cores and blocking
  read time) independently of the wall-clock execution `timeout`.
- **Timing mitigation**: secure-exec can freeze timers to blunt timing side
  channels.

These limits are real and enforced by secure-exec, but they are not yet
surfaced as `NodeRuntime.create()` options. The ergonomic `NodeRuntime` API
boots the VM with secure-exec's defaults for them; only the execution
`timeout` is configurable per call today. To tune the other limits you set
`CreateVmConfig.limits` when driving the VM through the lower-level protocol.

`@secure-exec/typescript` runs the TypeScript compiler **inside the sandbox**. The compiler is projected into the VM and every compile and type-check happens in the guest, so untrusted TypeScript never executes (or compiles) on the host.

Running the compiler in the sandbox protects you from **CPU and memory amplification attacks**. Type-checking attacker-controlled source is itself a risk: a small, malicious type can make `tsc` spin for seconds or balloon its heap (recursive conditional types, deeply nested generics, and similar pathologies). Because the compiler runs in a disposable VM you control rather than in your host process, that blow-up is contained by the sandbox boundary, and you can bound each run with a `timeout`, instead of hanging or OOM-ing the host.

You compile typed source to JavaScript, run the emitted code in the sandbox, and get structured diagnostics back, all without the compiler ever touching the host.

## Install

```bash
npm install @secure-exec/typescript secure-exec
```

## Compiling and type-checking

```ts
import { createTypeScriptTools } from "@secure-exec/typescript";
import { NodeRuntime } from "secure-exec";

const tools = createTypeScriptTools();

// A typed snippet we want to compile and run inside the sandbox.
const typeScriptSource = `
interface Greeting {
  name: string;
  count: number;
}

const greeting: Greeting = { name: "secure-exec", count: 3 };
const lines: string[] = Array.from(
  { length: greeting.count },
  (_unused, index) => \`hello \${greeting.name} #\${index + 1}\`,
);

for (const line of lines) {
  console.log(line);
}
`;

// Step 1: compile TypeScript to JavaScript inside the sandbox.
const compiled = await tools.compileSource({
  sourceText: typeScriptSource,
  compilerOptions: { module: "ESNext", target: "ES2022" },
});

if (!compiled.success) {
  const messages = compiled.diagnostics.map((d) => d.message);
  throw new Error(`TypeScript compile failed:\n${messages.join("\n")}`);
}

console.log("Compiled TypeScript to JavaScript inside the sandbox.");

// Step 2: run the emitted JavaScript inside the sandbox.
const rt = await NodeRuntime.create();
try {
  const result = await rt.exec(compiled.outputText ?? "");
  console.log("exitCode:", result.exitCode);
  console.log("guest stdout:\n" + result.stdout.trimEnd());
} finally {
  await rt.dispose();
}

// Step 3: type-check a snippet that has a type error inside the sandbox.
const typeCheck = await tools.typecheckSource({
  sourceText: `const total: number = "not a number";`,
});

console.log("type check success:", typeCheck.success);
for (const diagnostic of typeCheck.diagnostics) {
  console.log(
    `  ${diagnostic.category} TS${diagnostic.code} (line ${diagnostic.line}): ${diagnostic.message}`,
  );
}

if (typeCheck.success) {
  throw new Error("Expected the ill-typed snippet to fail type checking.");
}

console.log("OK: TypeScript compiled and type-checked inside the sandbox.");
```

*[See Full Example](https://github.com/rivet-dev/secure-exec/tree/main/examples/docs/feat-typescript)*

Running the example prints:

```
Compiled TypeScript to JavaScript inside the sandbox.
exitCode: 0
guest stdout:
hello secure-exec #1
hello secure-exec #2
hello secure-exec #3
type check success: false
  error TS2322 (line 1): Type 'string' is not assignable to type 'number'.
OK: TypeScript compiled and type-checked inside the sandbox.
```

## How it works

`createTypeScriptTools()` reads the `typescript` package on the host and projects it into the VM's virtual filesystem, then runs the compiler program in the guest through `secure-exec`. The compiler bundle is mounted (read lazily) rather than copied, so the multi-megabyte compiler is available in the sandbox without shipping its bytes up front. Each call boots a VM, runs the compiler inside it, and returns the result:

- **`compileSource({ sourceText, compilerOptions? })`** compiles a single TypeScript string and returns `{ success, diagnostics, outputText, sourceMapText }`. `outputText` is the emitted JavaScript, ready to run with `NodeRuntime`.
- **`typecheckSource({ sourceText })`** type-checks a single TypeScript string without emitting and returns `{ success, diagnostics }`.
- **`compileProject({ cwd?, configFilePath? })`** compiles a `tsconfig.json` project inside the VM and emits the output into the VM filesystem, returning `{ success, diagnostics, emitSkipped, emittedFiles }`.
- **`typecheckProject({ cwd?, configFilePath? })`** type-checks a `tsconfig.json` project inside the VM and returns `{ success, diagnostics }`.

Each diagnostic is `{ code, category, message, filePath?, line?, column? }`, so type errors come back as structured data you can inspect or report. To compile a project or point the tools at your own sources, seed files into the VM with the `files` option, or project a host directory with the `mounts` option:

```ts
const tools = createTypeScriptTools({
  files: {
    "/root/tsconfig.json": JSON.stringify({
      compilerOptions: { strict: true, target: "ES2022", module: "ESNext" },
      include: ["src"],
    }),
    "/root/src/index.ts": "export const answer: number = 42;\n",
  },
});

const result = await tools.compileProject({ cwd: "/root" });
```

Every VM boots with a **virtual filesystem** that lives entirely inside the kernel. Guest code creates directories, writes files, and lists them with the normal Node `fs` APIs, but none of that I/O ever touches the host disk. The guest sees an ordinary POSIX filesystem; the host sees nothing.

For basic filesystem usage (reading, writing, and listing files from guest code), see [Filesystem & Mounts](/docs/features/filesystem). This page focuses on the VFS model itself: how it isolates the guest, and the mount and storage backends behind it.

## Isolation from the host

The defining property of the virtual filesystem is isolation. A file the guest writes lives only in the kernel's virtual filesystem. When the host checks that same path, it finds nothing: the guest's writes never escape to the host disk. Each VM gets its own filesystem, and disposing the runtime with `rt.dispose()` tears it down.

The example below seeds a file into the VM at boot with `files`, writes another from the host with `rt.writeFile`, has the guest read both, reads one back on the host with `rt.readFile`, and then proves the guest path does not exist on the real host:

```ts
import { NodeRuntime } from "secure-exec";

// Boot a VM and seed a file into its virtual filesystem at boot with `files`.
// The bytes are copied into the kernel's in-memory filesystem; the host
// filesystem is never exposed to the guest.
const rt = await NodeRuntime.create({
	files: { "/home/user/seed.json": JSON.stringify({ ok: true }) },
});

try {
	// Write another file from the host with rt.writeFile, then have the guest
	// read both back. The guest only ever sees the virtual filesystem.
	await rt.writeFile("/home/user/note.txt", "written from the host\n");

	const result = await rt.run(`
		const { readFileSync } = await import("node:fs");
		const seed = JSON.parse(readFileSync("/home/user/seed.json", "utf8"));
		const note = readFileSync("/home/user/note.txt", "utf8").trim();
		console.log("guest read seed:", JSON.stringify(seed));
		console.log("guest read note:", note);
		globalThis.__return({ seed, note });
	`);

	console.log("guest stdout:", result.stdout.trim());
	console.log("guest exit code:", result.exitCode);
	console.log("value returned to host:", result.value);

	// Read a guest-written file back on the host with rt.readFile.
	const bytes = await rt.readFile("/home/user/seed.json");
	console.log("host rt.readFile:", new TextDecoder().decode(bytes));

	// The virtual filesystem is isolated from the host disk. The guest path does
	// not exist on the real host - prove it by checking the same path here.
	const { existsSync } = await import("node:fs");
	const guestPath = "/home/user/seed.json";
	console.log(
		`host sees ${guestPath}?`,
		existsSync(guestPath) ? "YES (unexpected!)" : "NO - isolated from host",
	);
} finally {
	await rt.dispose();
}
```

*[See Full Example](https://github.com/rivet-dev/secure-exec/tree/main/examples/docs/feat-virtual-filesystem)*

Running this prints:

```text
guest stdout: guest read seed: {"ok":true}
guest read note: written from the host
guest exit code: 0
value returned to host: { seed: { ok: true }, note: 'written from the host' }
host rt.readFile: {"ok":true}
host sees /home/user/seed.json? NO - isolated from host
```

This is the core guarantee of the virtual filesystem: guest code runs against a faithful POSIX filesystem, but every read and write is mediated by the kernel and stays inside the isolation boundary.

## Seeding and exchanging files

`NodeRuntime` gives you three ways to move data across the isolation boundary without exposing the host disk:

- **`create({ files })`** seeds files into the virtual filesystem before the guest runs, keyed by absolute guest path. Parent directories are created as needed. Use it to project fixtures, config, or npm packages into the sandbox. The bytes are copied into the VM's in-memory filesystem.
- **`rt.writeFile(path, data)`** writes a file into the VM after boot, creating parent directories as needed.
- **`rt.readFile(path)`** reads a file from the VM back to the host as raw bytes.

All three operate on the virtual filesystem only; the host filesystem is never touched.

## Custom and host-backed filesystems

The default `NodeRuntime.create()` filesystem is purely in-memory: it starts empty (apart from the bootstrapped root) and lives only for the life of the VM. That is not the only backing the kernel supports. Secure Exec mounts are pluggable, and several backends are real today.

- **Host directory mounts.** Project a real host directory into the VM with `NodeRuntime.create({ mounts })`. This is a first-class `NodeRuntime` option: see [Mounting host directories](/docs/features/filesystem#mounting-host-directories) for a runnable example. The mount is read-only by default and exposes only the chosen subtree to the guest.
- **Overlay filesystems.** The kernel can layer a writable filesystem over a read-only base, so guest writes land in the overlay and the base is never mutated. Overlays are configured at the mount/protocol layer rather than through a `NodeRuntime.create()` option.
- **Pluggable storage backends.** Remote and cloud-backed filesystems ship as separate packages that build a native mount plugin descriptor:
  - **`@secure-exec/s3`** (`createS3Backend`) backs a mount with an Amazon S3 bucket, so guest code reads and writes the bucket as an ordinary POSIX directory.
  - **`@secure-exec/google-drive`** (`createGoogleDriveBackend`) backs a mount with Google Drive, exposing Drive files to the guest as a POSIX directory.
  - **`@secure-exec/sandbox`** (`createSandboxFs`) backs a mount with a remote sandbox-agent host, scoping all guest filesystem operations under a base path on that host.

Host directory mounts are available directly through `NodeRuntime.create({ mounts })`. The overlay and remote storage backends are wired at the lower-level mount and descriptor layer: each storage package returns a mount plugin descriptor that is attached through the VM configuration (`configureVm` mounts) rather than through a one-line `create()` flag. They are real Secure Exec capabilities, driven through the protocol-level mount plumbing.

## Notes

- Guest code runs as an ES module. When you pass code to `rt.run(...)`, it is wrapped so that `globalThis.__return(...)` can hand a value back to the host. Because of that wrapping, use dynamic `await import("node:fs")` inside `run` code rather than a top-level `import` statement. (`rt.exec(...)`, which only captures stdout/stderr, runs your code as a plain module and accepts top-level `import`.)
- The default working directory is `/home/user`. Pass `cwd` to `NodeRuntime.create({ cwd })` to change it.
- File access is governed by the VM permission policy. By default the runtime allows the filesystem scope; tighten it by passing `permissions` to `NodeRuntime.create(...)`.

